member.name: T:Syncfusion.Web.UI.WebControls.Tools.GroupBarItemBinding
member.summary: Defines the relationship between a data item and the node it is binding to in a control.
member.remarks:
You can bind the properties of a item to a specific field by specifying groupbar item bindings. A GroupBarItemBinding object defines the relationship between each data item and the item that it is binding to.
The control stores its GroupBarItemBinding objects in the property and applies the bindings to the data source to create a one-to-one relationship between the groupbar hierarchy and the data source hierarchy. For each data item in the data source, the GroupBar control attempts to match the data item to a GroupBarItemBinding object in order to create the corresponding object.
When creating a GroupBarItemBinding object, you must specify the criteria for binding. The criteria indicates when a data item should be bound to a item. You can specify the DataMember property.
A data member specifies the type of the data item in the underlying data source, but can represent different information depending on the data source. Each data item in a hierarchical data source (represented by a interface) exposes a property, which specifies the type of the data item. For example, the data member for an XML element specifies the name of the element. When a data source contains multiple data item types, the data member specifies which data item type to use. The following GroupBarItemBinding declaration binds the Book elements of an XmlDataSource control to all the items in the groupbar, regardless of the location in the hierarchy, also binds the Name field of the data source to the property:
Once the binding criteria is established, you can then bind a property of a GroupBarItem object that can be bound to a value. You can bind to a field of a data item or to a static value. When bound to a static value, all GroupBarItem objects to which the GroupBarItemBinding object is applied share the same value.

member.name: T:Syncfusion.Web.UI.WebControls.Tools.MenuItemBinding
member.summary: Defines the relationship between a data item and the item it is binding to in a control.
member.remarks:
You can bind the properties of a item to a specific field by specifying Menu item bindings. A MenuItemBinding object defines the relationship between each data item and the item that it is binding to.
The control stores its MenuItemBinding objects in the property and applies the bindings to the data source to create a one-to-one relationship between the Menu hierarchy and the data source hierarchy. For each data item in the data source, the Menu control attempts to match the data item to a MenuItemBinding object in order to create the corresponding object.
When creating a MenuItemBinding object, you must specify the criteria for binding. The criteria indicates when a data item should be bound to a item. You can specify the DataMember property.
A data member specifies the type of the data item in the underlying data source, but can represent different information depending on the data source. Each data item in a hierarchical data source (represented by a interface) exposes a property, which specifies the type of the data item. For example, the data member for an XML element specifies the name of the element. When a data source contains multiple data item types, the data member specifies which data item type to use.
Once the binding criteria is established, you can then bind a property of a MenuItem object that can be bound to a value. You can bind to a field of a data item or to a static value. When bound to a static value, all MenuItem objects to which the MenuItemBinding object is applied share the same value.

member.name: F:Syncfusion.Web.UI.WebControls.Tools.SplitterResizeMode.AdjancentPane
member.summary: When split bar is moved to the left, the left adjacent pane width will be decreased and the right adjacent pane width will be increased.

member.name: F:Syncfusion.Web.UI.WebControls.Tools.SplitterResizeMode.EndPane
member.summary: When split bar is moved to the left, the left adjacent pane width will be decreased and the width of the right most pane in the splitter will be increased.

member.name: F:Syncfusion.Web.UI.WebControls.Tools.SplitterResizeMode.Proportional
member.summary: All panes that are positioned in the direction where the split bar is moved will decrease their width/height, depending on their current width/height, and the pane that is adjacent in the opposite direction will increase its width/height.

member.name: T:Syncfusion.Web.UI.WebControls.Tools.SplitterBarCollapseMode
member.summary: Specifies the collapse mode of a splitbar.

member.name: F:Syncfusion.Web.UI.WebControls.Tools.SplitterBarCollapseMode.None
member.summary: Will not display collapse buttons, the adjacent panes will not be collapsible.

member.name: F:Syncfusion.Web.UI.WebControls.Tools.SplitterBarCollapseMode.Forward
member.summary: Depending on the Layout property of the parent splitter, the splitter bar will display either left-to-right or top-to-bottom collapse button. When the user clicks the button, the left (top) adjacent pane will increase its size with the width/height of the right (bottom) adjacent pane.

member.name: F:Syncfusion.Web.UI.WebControls.Tools.SplitterBarCollapseMode.Backward
member.summary: Depending on the Layout property of the parent splitter, the splitter bar will display either right-to-left or bottom-to-top collapse button. When the user clicks the button, the right (bottom) adjacent pane will increase its size with the width/height of the left (top) adjacent pane.

member.name: F:Syncfusion.Web.UI.WebControls.Tools.SplitterBarCollapseMode.Both
member.summary: Will display both buttons for Forward and Backward collapsing.

member.summary: Represents a item in the control.
member.remarks: The TabStrip control is made up of a hierarchy of panel items represented by TabStripItem objects. Panel items at the top level (level 0) are called root panel items. A panel item that has a parent panel item is called child item. All root panel items are stored in the collection of the TabStrip control. Child items are stored in a parent panel item's collection.

member.name: T:Syncfusion.Web.UI.WebControls.Tools.TabStripItemBinding
member.summary: Defines the relationship between a data item and the item it is binding to in a control.
member.remarks: You can bind the properties of a item to a specific field by specifying TabStrip item bindings. A TabStripItemBinding object defines the relationship between each data item and the item that it is binding to. The control stores its TabStripItemBinding objects in the property and applies the bindings to the data source to create a one-to-one relationship between the TabStrip hierarchy and the data source hierarchy. For each data item in the data source, the TabStrip control attempts to match the data item to a TabStripItemBinding object in order to create the corresponding object. When creating a TabStripItemBinding object, you must specify the criteria for binding. The criteria indicates when a data item should be bound to a item. You can specify the DataMember property. A data member specifies the type of the data item in the underlying data source, but can represent different information depending on the data source. Each data item in a hierarchical data source (represented by a interface) exposes a property, which specifies the type of the data item. For example, the data member for an XML element specifies the name of the element. When a data source contains multiple data item types, the data member specifies which data item type to use. Once the binding criteria is established, you can then bind a property of a TabStripItem object that can be bound to a value. You can bind to a field of a data item or to a static value. When bound to a static value, all TabStripItem objects to which the TabStripItemBinding object is applied share the same value.

member.name: T:Syncfusion.Web.UI.WebControls.Tools.ToolBarItemBinding
member.summary: Defines the relationship between a data item and the node it is binding to in a control.
member.remarks:
You can bind the properties of a item to a specific field by specifying ToolBar node bindings. A ToolBarItemBinding object defines the relationship between each data item and the node that it is binding to.
The control stores its ToolBarItemBinding objects in the property and applies the bindings to the data source to create a one-to-one relationship between the ToolBar hierarchy and the data source hierarchy. For each data item in the data source, the ToolBar control attempts to match the data item to a ToolBarItemBinding object in order to create the corresponding ToolBarNode object.
When creating a ToolBarItemBinding object, you must specify the criteria for binding. The criteria indicates when a data item should be bound to a node. You can specify the DataMember property.
A data member specifies the type of the data item in the underlying data source, but can represent different information depending on the data source. Each data item in a hierarchical data source (represented by a interface) exposes a property, which specifies the type of the data item. For example, the data member for an XML element specifies the name of the element. When a data source contains multiple data item types, the data member specifies which data item type to use.
Once the binding criteria is established, you can then bind a property of a ToolBarNode object that can be bound to a value. You can bind to a field of a data item or to a static value. When bound to a static value, all ToolBarNode objects to which the ToolBarItemBinding object is applied share the same value.

member.name: T:Syncfusion.Web.UI.WebControls.Tools.TreeViewItemBinding
member.summary: Defines the relationship between a data item and the node it is binding to in a control.
member.remarks:
You can bind the properties of a item to a specific field by specifying TreeView node bindings. A TreeViewItemBinding object defines the relationship between each data item and the node that it is binding to.
The control stores its TreeViewItemBinding objects in the property and applies the bindings to the data source to create a one-to-one relationship between the TreeView hierarchy and the data source hierarchy. For each data item in the data source, the TreeView control attempts to match the data item to a TreeViewItemBinding object in order to create the corresponding object.
When creating a TreeViewItemBinding object, you must specify the criteria for binding. The criteria indicates when a data item should be bound to a node. You can specify the DataMember property.
A data member specifies the type of the data item in the underlying data source, but can represent different information depending on the data source. Each data item in a hierarchical data source (represented by a interface) exposes a property, which specifies the type of the data item. For example, the data member for an XML element specifies the name of the element. When a data source contains multiple data item types, the data member specifies which data item type to use.
Once the binding criteria is established, you can then bind a property of a TreeViewNode object that can be bound to a value. You can bind to a field of a data item or to a static value. When bound to a static value, all TreeViewNode objects to which the TreeViewItemBinding object is applied share the same value.

/// Represents a collection of objects in the control.
The TreeViewItemBindingCollection class is used to store and manage a collection of TreeViewItemBinding objects in the TreeView control. The TreeView control uses the TreeViewItemBindingCollection class for its property. The DataBindings property contains TreeViewItemBinding objects that define the relationship between a data item and the item that it is binding to.
